22
00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:28.000
Pedro: kind of default that you have account abstraction as an EOA. So, with H141, you're basically thinking as every wallet on Ethereum will be account abstracted by default, they just need to start using a new transaction type.

23
00:11:28.190 --> 00:11:38.549
Pedro: But the problem with this is because 8141 is essentially a general pre-computation. Essentially, you can think of…

24
00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:56.959
Pedro: Ethereum provides you with computation on settlements, and with 8.1.4.1, you have, like, this pre-execution computation. So you have these programmable accounts that can do some validation before the transaction actually gets settled on-chain.

25
00:11:57.160 --> 00:12:11.170
Pedro: That meant that we need to have some sort of framework of how we can design this programmability, and how we can build smart accounts for all of these EOAs. And right now, there is a…

26
00:12:11.270 --> 00:12:23.220
Pedro: a default for how we submit transactions, which they're being called frame transactions for native account abstraction, but there's no default for how you actually build your Smart Accounts.

27
00:12:23.300 --> 00:12:28.420
Pedro: Fortunately, Fortune 3-7 is 3 years old, so there's been a lot of work being done on this.

28
00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:41.930
Pedro: And in my opinion, and I think Shiran would share this as well, the best approach with actually building a smart account in a standardized way has been ERC7579.

29
00:12:41.930 --> 00:12:53.729
Pedro: ERC779 is essentially a very minimal modular account system that allows you to essentially build your smart account programmability. However, 7579 has always been designed around

30
00:12:53.730 --> 00:13:05.829
Pedro: the premise that it is to be designed with Fortune 3.7 account abstraction. So what it would look like if you build a minimal modular account for 8.1.4.1.

31
00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:23.310
