37
00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:06.280
Chiranjeev Mishra: smart accounts. Like, in 4337, you had that iAccount set up.

38
00:14:06.370 --> 00:14:25.379
Chiranjeev Mishra: But for frames, we don't have it yet. So this ERC basically discussed on how we can use the existing 7579 account standards, which basically has this whole ecosystem of modules and the whole modularity setup. So it's basically an extension to 7579.

39
00:14:25.730 --> 00:14:34.479
Chiranjeev Mishra: On how you can use frame, transaction-based accounts, and still, have the modularity of 7579.

40
00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:42.939
Chiranjeev Mishra: So… if the… if we discuss on, like, how it's different from, 7579, it's…

41
00:14:43.180 --> 00:15:00.819
Chiranjeev Mishra: practically the same, but the validation and execution rules change a little bit, because the frame transactions act in a different way, with the new opcode called Approve, and the sender frames now being enshrined on the protocol level, rather on the contract level.

42
00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:05.540
Chiranjeev Mishra: So, yeah, that's the premise of this whole, standard.

43
00:15:05.770 --> 00:15:09.979
Chiranjeev Mishra: So, like, describing on how a frame account would look like.

44
00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:22.139
Chiranjeev Mishra: So, basically, this one. Yeah. So, ERC8286 frame account, which basically implements the 7579 account config and the module config.

45
00:15:25.020 --> 00:15:36.309
Chiranjeev Mishra: Yeah, so, we introduced something called, supports approval mode. So, in 7579, they just had supports execution mode.

46
00:15:36.410 --> 00:15:51.430
Chiranjeev Mishra: Because the 4337 didn't have a concept of, like, approval lists or something, but Frame Transactions does. So they have a set of approvals, like, they can approve for execution if an account can be approved for payments.

47
00:15:51.450 --> 00:15:57.210
Chiranjeev Mishra: So that's why, account need to determine, like, what all approval modes they want to support.

48
00:15:57.950 --> 00:16:01.920
Chiranjeev Mishra: So, this is the main addition, I would say.

49
00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:05.560
Chiranjeev Mishra: To… on top of 7579.

50
00:16:06.350 --> 00:16:13.260
Chiranjeev Mishra: Yeah, and… We have specified the execution rules, the validation rules.

51
00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:16.260
Chiranjeev Mishra: Like, like, how would a…

52
00:16:16.550 --> 00:16:28.540
Chiranjeev Mishra: frame validator would look like, which is in here. Now, they would have this function called a validate frame, so any 7579 module, if they want to behave like a

53
00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:37.869
Chiranjeev Mishra: like, a frame validator. So, we, Alex actually introduced a new module type here, a new module ID called

54
00:16:37.950 --> 00:16:44.950
Chiranjeev Mishra: I mean, it's up to, like, the protocol and what to decide, what the module type would be.

55
00:16:45.160 --> 00:16:55.009
Chiranjeev Mishra: But, yeah, so this 8141 frame validator is a module that basically decides the approval mode a transaction is entitled to.

56
00:16:56.260 --> 00:17:08.100
Chiranjeev Mishra: So, yeah, any 7, any, module builder can basically implement this iframe validator, which in turn implement the 7579 model standards.

